<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n54127g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54127g">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54127g"> 127(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> nitric &amp; potash / solidpewter <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54127g"><li>FW 167.21 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fd/lexfd.htm#n54127g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fd/l39fd.htm#n54127g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54127g">MS BL 47476a-244</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:505 <a name=""fad8" href="../../FF/fdra/fda.htm#"fad8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fd/fdd7.htm#n54127g">Draft: I.6&sect;4.7</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Take a little caustic potash solution and add litmus to it, then gently pour some nitric acid in; the blue litmus will soon turn red, because the acid neutralizes the alkali. If the water be now boiled away in a small porcelain basin, a white salt will be left which is nitre or <mark>saltpetre</mark>, made by the chemical combination of <mark>nitric acid and potash</mark>, the substance which we originally used to make the nitric acid; and if after heating it strongly you dissolve a little of this salt in water, the solution will neither turn red litmus blue, nor blue litmus red: this shows that the salt is neutral. <small> H. E. Roscoe, <a name="HERC1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#HERC1"><cite title="source">Science Primer: Chemistry</cite></a> (n.d.) 81</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Solid pewter. Salt petre: potassium nitrate. The chief constituent of gunpowder. </mm> </dd></dl>
